<HEAD>King Resignation Prompts Allegations of Unrest</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURAN NEERGAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The youngest son of slain civil rights leader
<ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION> has resigned as president of the center that
carries his father's name amid talk of a rift among the leadership
over the center's direction.
   <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON>'s resignation was announced <DATE>Thursday</DATE> by the <ORGANIZATION>Martin
Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center for <ORGANIZATION>Nonviolent Social Change</ORGANIZATION>, but no reason
was given.
   Civil rights leaders in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> said <PERSON>King</PERSON> stepped down because
of conflicts over fiscal and personnel concerns, and there were
reports of a rift between <PERSON>King</PERSON> and his mother, <PERSON>Coretta Scott King</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>Atlanta City</LOCATION> Councilman <PERSON>Hosea Williams</PERSON> said the center was
encroaching on the leadership position in the civil rights movement
of the <ORGANIZATION>Southern Christian Leadership Conference</ORGANIZATION>, which the elder
King founded.
   ``The center's purpose was to perpetuate the legacy of <PERSON>Dr. King</PERSON>,
but not to carry on the whole movement,'' said <PERSON>Williams</PERSON>, a former
lieutenant of the elder King. ``When they started talking about
leading the movement, freeing black folk, they started competing,
and both got hurt.''
   Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON>, who was an aide to the elder King in the
'60s, was quoted by <ORGANIZATION>The Atlanta Journal-Constitution</ORGANIZATION> as saying the
resignation was part of a family dispute fueled by a generation gap.
   A King Center official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said <PERSON>Mrs. King</PERSON> might return to the presidency she relinquished to
her son.
   The <ORGANIZATION>King Center</ORGANIZATION> is a non-profit organization devoted to
education about <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s teachings and philosophy. It also urges
action on international racial issues, especially apartheid in
<LOCATION>South Africa</LOCATION>, and is host to the annual <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION>
birthday week celebration.
   The <ORGANIZATION>SCLC</ORGANIZATION> has taken an activist approach to the problems of
poverty and racism since it was founded in <DATE>1957</DATE> by King and the
Revs. <PERSON>Joseph Lowery</PERSON>, <PERSON>Ralph Abernathy</PERSON> and <PERSON>Fred Shuttlesworth</PERSON>.
   ``We are the activist arm of the movement,'' <PERSON>Lowery</PERSON> has said.
``When you do that, you step on toes and you don't become the most
popular kid on the block.''
   The Rev. <PERSON>Jesse Jackson</PERSON>, a follower of King in the <DATE>1960s</DATE> and a
former candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination, said
in a telephone interview from <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> that the two groups are
complementary rather than competitive.
   ``The fact that <PERSON>Dr. King</PERSON> remains a frame of reference for
justice is mainly that his work has been institutionalized,''
<PERSON>Jackson</PERSON> said, referring to the center.
   ``The <ORGANIZATION>SCLC</ORGANIZATION>'s legacy (is) direct action, challenging the racism,
challenging anti-semitism,'' he added.
   <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON>, 28, was elected in <DATE>January</DATE> to take over from his
mother, who remained as chief executive officer. He said he wanted
to cut the center's dependency on donations and put it on a solid
financial base so it could ``market and disseminate'' non-violent
teachings.
   King could not be reached at the office of his business,
<ORGANIZATION>Visionary Development Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   In a statement from the <ORGANIZATION>King Center</ORGANIZATION>, board Chairman <PERSON>Jesse Hill
Jr.</PERSON> did not address the reasons for <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s decision.
   ``It must be borne in mind that the changing circumstances,
staff and management changes and tragic assassinations have not
changed this eternal commitment to social change through creative
love and revolutionary non-violence,'' Hill wrote.
   The King Center, on <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>'s historic <LOCATION>Auburn Avenue</LOCATION>, contains a
museum and <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION>'s tomb.
</TEXT>
