<HEAD>Deputy Assigned to Provide Security for King Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy has been assigned to provide security
for the family of <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION> for the past five months,
a measure defended by the county sheriff as a valid use of tax
money.
   ``I'd say it's public money going to protect a public family,''
<LOCATION>Fulton County</LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON>Richard Lankford</PERSON> was quoted as saying in
today's editions of The <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> Constitution. ``Anything that
happened to the <PERSON>King</PERSON> family at this juncture would become
international.''
   King was assassinated <DATE>April 4, 1968</DATE>, in <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn</LOCATION>. His
mother, <PERSON>Alberta King</PERSON>, was shot to death in <DATE>1975</DATE> while playing the
organ for a <DATE>Sunday</DATE> service in an <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> church.
   ``It would be an indictment, I think, against our community if
another tragedy would befall the family,'' the sheriff said in
acknowledging he assigned deputy <PERSON>Angelo Willoughby</PERSON> to the post.
   The newspaper said it learned of the deputy's hiring through
county records.
   County Manager <PERSON>Sam Brownlee</PERSON> said the county commission should
have been asked to approve the assignment because it amounts to
publicly financed protection for a private family.
   ``That is not something the <ORGANIZATION>Board of Commissioners</ORGANIZATION> has
authorized,'' he said. ``That's something the sheriff has done.''
   Willoughby reports daily to the <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center
for Non-violent Social Change.
   ``I don't know if I would say he's a bodyguard, but he's there
for the protection of the family as well as for the security of the
center itself,'' <PERSON>Lankford</PERSON> said.
   The civil rights leader's son, <ORGANIZATION>Fulton County Commissioner Martin
Luther King III</ORGANIZATION>, said he appreciates the officer's presence.
   ``I carry the name <PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON> and that draws
crackpots,'' he said.
   ``A guy came up and approached my mother (<ORGANIZATION>Coretta Scott King</ORGANIZATION>)
last week,'' <PERSON>King</PERSON> said. ``He was just crazy. If he (<PERSON>Willoughby</PERSON>) had
not been there, something might have happened. Once he saw a police
official there, he backed off.''
</TEXT>
