<HEAD>Bill Providing King Holiday Passes in Idaho</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Idaho House</ORGANIZATION> approved legislation
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> to make <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION> the 47th state with a holiday honoring
slain civil rights leader <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> voted 53-27 for the bill previously passed by the
<ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>. Later, the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> accepted a <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> amendment that made the
holiday's complete name ``Martin Luther King Jr.-Idaho Human Rights
Day.''
   Final approval by the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> was expected <DATE>Thursday</DATE> before the
bill goes to Gov. <PERSON>Cecil Andrus</PERSON>, who proposed the holiday.
   The bill was the subject of tortuous arguments in the
legislature last week. Opponents said their constituents didn't
care about <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We're told this isn't a black holiday, but yet we're also told
we can't change the name,'' said Rep. <PERSON>Stan Hawkins</PERSON>, a Republican.
``If you really have a guilt trip in mind by passing this, you're
making a mistake.''
   Rep. <PERSON>L. Ed Brown</PERSON>, also a Republican and one of the bill's
sponsors, said the decision on the bill would ``say more about
<LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION> than .. about <PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON>.''
   ``<LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION> is not the state in the <LOCATION>Union</LOCATION> that's going to determine
<PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON>'s greatness,'' <PERSON>Brown</PERSON> said. ``Forty-six states
and the federal government have already done that.''
   <PERSON>Brown</PERSON> said adopting a King holiday would ``send a very special
message to future generations about how Idahoans feel about
minorities.''
   Besides <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION>, only <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Montana</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Hampshire</LOCATION> have not
adopted state holidays corresponding with the federal holiday
honoring King on the third <DATE>Monday</DATE> in <DATE>January</DATE>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Idaho Legislature</ORGANIZATION> created a state commemorative day in <DATE>1987</DATE>,
and a bill creating a state holiday died in a <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> committee last
year despite arguments its failure would only reinforce the
perception some have of <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION> as a haven for racists.
   Opponents said they objected to another day off for government
employees. Proponents said <LOCATION>Idaho</LOCATION>'s economy would suffer through
lost tourism and convention business if it failed to establish the
holiday.
</TEXT>
