<HEAD>Civil Rights Center Won't Confirm Reported Resignation of King's
Son</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center for <ORGANIZATION>Non-Violent
Social Change</ORGANIZATION> has refused to confirm or deny reports that the civil
rights leader's 28-year-old son is resigning as center president.
   A source within the civil rights community, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that differences over how the
center should be managed prompted <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON> and executive
director <PERSON>Barbara Williams-Skinner</PERSON> to decide to resign. The source
did not say what those differences were.
   <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON> was named president in <DATE>January</DATE> and officially took
office <DATE>April 4</DATE>, the anniversary of his father's assassination,
saying he wanted to place the center on a solid financial base and
cut its dependency on donations.
   Messages seeking comment from King at his entertainment company,
<ORGANIZATION>Visionary Development Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, and his home were not returned, nor
were calls to at least six <ORGANIZATION>King Center</ORGANIZATION> board members.
   The board said it would issue ``a definitive statement at an
appropriate time.''
   The <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> Journal-Constitution reported that <PERSON>Ms.
Williams-Skinner</PERSON> was said to have clashed with <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON>'s aunt,
<PERSON>Christine King Farris</PERSON>, who controls the center's finances, over
budgetary and program proposals.
   The newspaper also quoted Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON> as characterizing
the reported resignation as a family dispute fueled by normal
tension between generations. <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON>Coretta Scott
King</PERSON>, is the center's chief executive officer.
   Young, a lieutenant of <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr.</ORGANIZATION> during the <DATE>1960s</DATE>,
was among board members of the center who received copies of a
letter of <PERSON>Dexter King</PERSON>'s resignation, The <ORGANIZATION>New York Times</ORGANIZATION> reported
today.
   City Councilman <PERSON>Hosea Williams</PERSON>, another former King lieutenant,
said the center recently had placed itself in competition with the
<ORGANIZATION>Southern Christian Leadership Conference</ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King</ORGANIZATION>
founded, for leadership of the civil rights movement.
   ``The center's purpose was to perpetuate the legacy of <PERSON>Dr. King</PERSON>,
but not to carry on the whole movement,'' <PERSON>Williams</PERSON> said. ``When
they started talking about leading the movement, freeing black
folk, they started competing, and both got hurt.''
   <PERSON>Williams</PERSON> said center staff members told him of conflict and
asked for his help in resolving it, ``but I told them I wasn't in a
position to get involved, because people would interpret that as I
was anti-Mrs. King.''
</TEXT>
