<HEAD>Educators Discuss Formation and Propagation of Curriculum on King
Holiday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators gathered <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to grapple with the
practical and philosophical problems that would confront teachers
in developing a kindergarten-12th grade curriculum on the national
holiday honoring slain civil rights leader <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``If we teach the principles of nonviolent social change to the
kids from kindergarten, what do we do when they stage a walkout?''
one educator asked.
   The answer, from <PERSON>Harold Sims</PERSON> of the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther
King Center</ORGANIZATION> for Non-Violent Social Change: ``You have to teach them
the principles of non-violent social change, let them know that
civil disobedience was the last step following long period of
negotiation.''
   Teaching dilemmas, parental reaction, lack of course materials,
training and faculty support were some of the issues raised during
the mini-convention on ``Infusing Educational Materials Related to
<PERSON>Martin Luther King Jr.</PERSON>, into the Curriculum of the <ORGANIZATION>Nation</ORGANIZATION>'s
Schools'' sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION>Education Committee of the Federal
Holiday Commission</ORGANIZATION> and the King center.
   Committee members included <ORGANIZATION>National Education Association</ORGANIZATION>
President <PERSON>Mary Futrell</PERSON>; Sister <PERSON>Catherine McNamee</PERSON>, president of the
<ORGANIZATION>National Catholic Educational Association</ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON>Manya Ungar</PERSON>, president
of the <ORGANIZATION>National Parents and Teachers Association</ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON>Lawrence
Davenport</PERSON>, assistant secretary of the <ORGANIZATION>Department of Energy</ORGANIZATION>, and
<PERSON>Mrs. Christine King Farris</PERSON>, <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s sister.
   Saying she hoped this would be ``the first of many,''
conferences designed to make available audio-visual materials,
training programs and other classroom aids, <PERSON>Futrell</PERSON> said, ``You
cannot simply go out and say `I'm going to teach about the life of
<PERSON>Dr. King</PERSON>' unless you know about his life, unless you understand and
have resources available.''
   <PERSON>Futrell</PERSON> said the purpose of the convention was to give the
participants an opportunity to come together and ``talk about how
we teach about King and how we inculcate that into the curriculum.''
   Many of the speakers discussed the problems associated with
their particular constituent groups.
   ``One problem is that no one has ever been really taught about
King,'' said <PERSON>Gordon Ambach</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Council of Chief State School
Officers</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``You have to recognize that an association like mine is _
predominantly white, Anglo-Saxon, Protestant, middle class and
suburban,'' said <PERSON>Ungar</PERSON> of the national <ORGANIZATION>PTA</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``The board members with which I deal ... are not reflective of
the greater society _ particularly that portion of society which
increasingly has problems getting their voices heard and their
agenda addressed,'' she said.
   She noted that her group was reaching out to other
organizations, such as the Anti-Defamation League, to help produce
literature by next <DATE>June</DATE>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>PTA</ORGANIZATION> board, which prepared itself through training in human
relation skills and a task force for inclusiveness, suggested that
the state and local chapters initiate programs which ``demonstrate
a commitment to the things that <PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON> espoused and
stood for,'' she said.
   ``To do this, the parents have got to educate themselves and
find out who <PERSON>Martin Luther King</PERSON> was,'' <PERSON>Ungar</PERSON> said. ``We hope to
have literature aimed at the parents, talking about how we either
overtly or covertly teach prejudice, teach racism or perpetuate
this cycle of hatred and violence,'' she said.
</TEXT>
