<HEAD>Japanese Prime Minister Visits Grave of Martin Luther King Jr.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Last 6 grafs EMBARGOED until 8 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister <PERSON>Toshiki Kaifu</PERSON> urged his
countrymen to be ``good corporate citizens'' in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>
and proposed a broad cultural exchange between the two countries.
   Kaifu, the first Japanese prime minister to tour the Southeast,
also placed a flower wreath at the tomb of the Rev. <PERSON>Martin Luther
King Jr.</PERSON> and met <DATE>Thursday</DATE> with the slain civil rights leader's
widow.
   ``He greatly admired <PERSON>Dr. King</PERSON>. It's only natural he would come
here,'' said <PERSON>Stephen Allen</PERSON>, public relations officer for the
<ORGANIZATION>Japanese Consulate</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>. ``<LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> is committed to human rights
around the world.''
   Coretta <PERSON>Scott King King</PERSON> took <PERSON>Kaifu</PERSON> on a brief tour of the <ORGANIZATION>Martin
Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center for <ORGANIZATION>Nonviolent Social Change</ORGANIZATION> and gave him
several mementos, said <PERSON>Steve Klein</PERSON>, the center's research associate.
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> civil rights advocates were outraged four years ago when
then-Prime Minister <PERSON>Yasuhiro Nakasone</PERSON> said blacks and Hispanics
lowered the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> intelligence standard.
   ``He's a new prime minister. We can't hold him responsible for
what others have said,'' <PERSON>Klein</PERSON> said.
   ``The <ORGANIZATION>American Southeast</ORGANIZATION> has long had good relations with <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>,
