<HEAD>Monthlong King Pilgrimage to Wind Up in Atlanta Today</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rally scheduled for 2 p.m.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month-long, multi-state journey that began on
the 20th anniversary of the assassination of the Rev. <PERSON>Martin Luther
King Jr.</PERSON> was headed for the city of his birth today to close with a
``Jobs with Justice'' rally.
   Thousands of civil rights activists, church congregants and
labor union members were expected to join the group of about 30
marchers at the <TIME>afternoon</TIME> rally at the <ORGANIZATION>Atlanta Civic Center</ORGANIZATION>,
organizers said.
   The pilgrimage, organized by the <ORGANIZATION>Southern Christian Leadership
Conference</ORGANIZATION> founded by <PERSON>King</PERSON>, started in <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn.</LOCATION>, on <DATE>April 5</DATE> _
one day after a memorial service there in memory of the slain civil
rights leader.
   The Rev. <PERSON>Joseph Lowery</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>SCLC</ORGANIZATION>, said at the
outset that he wanted to draw attention to the plight of the poor,
which was a major concern of <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s at the time of his death.
   ``We're trying to stir up the countryside,'' <PERSON>Lowery</PERSON> said.
``We're trying to bring people out to express their outrage about
poverty.''
   Atlanta Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON>, who was a close aide to <PERSON>King</PERSON>, was
scheduled to welcome the rally today. Among the scheduled speakers
were <PERSON>Lowery</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> Commissioner of Agriculture <PERSON>Jim Hightower</PERSON> and a
representative of the <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center for <ORGANIZATION>Nonviolent
Social Change</ORGANIZATION>. Folk singers <PERSON>Peter</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Paul &amp; Mary</ORGANIZATION> were expected to
perform.
   King was fatally shot on a balcony of the <PERSON>Lorraine Motel</PERSON> in
<LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION> on <DATE>April 4, 1968</DATE>.
   The pilgrimage, which started with about 30 marchers, has
included marches and rallies in towns along the route through
<LOCATION>Alabama</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Georgia</LOCATION> on the way to <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION>, <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s birthplace. Most
of the trail has been covered in vans, with short marches at each
destination.
</TEXT>
