<HEAD>Civil Rights Leaders Applaud Ouster Of Mecham</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note 9th graf, which may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ouster of <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON>Evan Mecham</PERSON>, who
canceled a state holiday honoring civil rights crusader <PERSON>Martin
Luther King Jr.</PERSON>, was cheered by hundreds at a banquet commemorating
<PERSON>King</PERSON>'s assassination 20 years ago.
   <ORGANIZATION>Southern Christian Leadership Conference</ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON>Joseph Lowery</PERSON>
announced <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON>'s conviction by the <ORGANIZATION>Arizona Senate</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>Monday</DATE> at the
awards dinner that night.
   About 750 people cheered and applauded as the civil rights
anthem, ``We Shall Overcome,'' played softly in the background.
   ``I hate to rejoice,'' <PERSON>Lowery</PERSON> said, ``but I feel good about this
... We did overcome. Justice has been served.''
   Mecham was removed from office 20 years to the day that <PERSON>King</PERSON>,
who founded the <ORGANIZATION>SCLC</ORGANIZATION>, was shot to death in <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Tenn</LOCATION>.
   Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON>, an aide to King and an ordained
Congregationalist minister, reacted to the news with a Bible verse:
``Whatsoever a man soweth, that shall he also reap.''
   In <LOCATION>Altamont</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Utah</LOCATION>, meanwhile, where <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON> grew up, his removal
from office was lamented by relatives and some old acquaintances.
   ``It's just a dirty deal and Mafia-headed. He has just been
blackballed. I think it's disgusting,'' said his cousin <ORGANIZATION>Ona</ORGANIZATION> Rust of
<LOCATION>Altamont</LOCATION>. ``I'm very disappointed in the people of <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION>.''
   Mecham graduated from <ORGANIZATION>Altamont High School</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1942</DATE> and moved
away after joining the service in <DATE>1943</DATE>. He is scheduled to address
the high school's commencement ceremony <DATE>May 27</DATE>.
   A former classmate, <LOCATION>Beverly Fieldsted</LOCATION>, who was one year behind
<PERSON>Mecham</PERSON> in high school, said <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON>'s removal must stem from a
misunderstanding and the former governor is innocent.
   Mecham canceled a King holiday for state workers on <DATE>Jan. 12,
1987</DATE>, angering civil rights leaders and triggering a boycott by
some organizations that had planned conventions and by some rock
groups.
   He went on to anger blacks, Jews, women and homosexuals with
official actions or offhand remarks.
   Among other things, he defended the use of the word
``pickaninny'' for black children.
   ``I think Gov. <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON> exhibited insensitivity, a corruption of
spirit,'' <PERSON>Lowery</PERSON> said in an interview. ``I think it had to be a
corruption of spirit in order to insult <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King</ORGANIZATION> and the
birthday holiday which the nation wanted to honor.''
   King's widow, <PERSON>Coretta Scott King</PERSON>, stood thoughtfully after being
told of <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON>'s impeachment, and declined to comment.
   The <ORGANIZATION>SCLC</ORGANIZATION> dinner was held to present the group's annual <ORGANIZATION>Martin
Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Memorial Drum Major for <ORGANIZATION>Justice Awards</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
