<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Coretta Scott King renews Martin Luther King Jr.'s plea for
non-violence.; PHOTO: (Martin Luther King Jr.)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  ..; PAST; BLACK; RELIGION; CIVIL; RIGHT; LEADER; BIRTH; DATE; ANNIVERSARY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  AS THE nation observes the sixth Martin Luther King Jr. holiday today, the war
in the Persian Gulf challenges us to examine his views on militarism.;    This
may be a difficult task for many Americans. As Dr. Vincent Harding of the
Iliff School of Theology explains, "The Martin King of 1963 . . . is a more
comfortable image for us all -- (he is) the triumphant Martin Luther King Jr.
of the March on Washington, calling a nation and a world to a magnificent
dream of human solidarity."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PREACHING PEACE
KING'S CHALLENGE TO FEED THE POOR, NOT FOREIGN
WARS, ECHOES TODAY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story
Coretta Scott King is chief executive officer of the Martin Luther King Jr.
Center for Non-violent Social Change. This article was distributed by United
Feature Syndicate Inc.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Yet, as <PERSON>Dr. Harding</PERSON> points out, the <PERSON>Martin Luther King Jr.</PERSON> of <DATE>1967</DATE> had seen
the prospects for fulfilling his dream shattered by the nation's deepening
involvement in the <LOCATION>Vietnam War.</LOCATION>;    On <DATE>April 4, 1967</DATE> -- exactly one year
before he was assassinated -- <PERSON>Martin</PERSON> condemned <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military involvement in
the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War in a speech at <LOCATION>New York City</LOCATION>'s Riverside Church:;    "A few
years ago . . . it seemed as if there was a real promise of hope for the
poor," he said, referring to President <PERSON>Lyndon Johnson</PERSON>'s War on Poverty. "There
were experiments, hopes, new beginnings. Then came the buildup in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>, and
I watched the program broken and eviscerated. . . . I knew that <LOCATION>America</LOCATION> would
never invest the funds and energies in the rehabilitation of its poor so long
as adventures like <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> continued to draw men and skills and money like
some demoniacal destructive suction tube.";    He expressed his deep
disappointment that the <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> War caused the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to "increase our
troop commitments in support of governments which were singularly corrupt,
inept and without popular support.";    When <PERSON>Martin</PERSON> later stated that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
government had become "the greatest purveyor of violence in the world today,"
he drew widespread criticism, even from some of his supporters.;    But my
husband had told the painful truth -- for no other government had sent a
half-million troops to intervene on behalf of a brutal, corrupt dictatorship
that was thousands of miles from its own boundaries. No other government had
squandered many <MONEY>billions of dollars</MONEY> on the weapons of destruction while
millions of its own people languished in poverty, homelessness and
malnutrition. He warned that our intervention in <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> was a symptom of a
"far deeper malady" that would lead the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> into future wars. And he
called for a unilateral cease-fire and the withdrawal of all foreign troops.; 
  The <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> is not <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>. But <PERSON>Martin</PERSON>'s criticism of the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
government's proneness for military adventurism remains particularly relevant
in <DATE>1991.</DATE>;    <DATE>Today</DATE>, we might ask ourselves the question he asked in <DATE>1967</DATE>: "Why
has our nation placed itself in the position of being God's military agent on
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>? . . . Why have we substituted the arrogant undertaking of policing the
whole world for the high task of putting our own house in order?";    Before
the war broke, the <ORGANIZATION>Center for Defense Information</ORGANIZATION> estimated that military
aggression against <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> could cost taxpayers <MONEY>$140 billion</MONEY> in the year ahead.
It also is estimated that each day of war in the gulf will cost four times the
amount of our annual contribution to the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations.</ORGANIZATION>;    The human cost of
war will be even greater; 20,000 Americans could lose their lives, according
to one estimate.;    Military spending was out of control even before the
crisis in the gulf. When you subtract self-funding accounts such as Social
Security from the federal budget, our government is spending <MONEY>55 cents</MONEY> out of
every taxpayer dollar on the military. This compares with just <MONEY>two cents</MONEY> for
education.;    Excessive military spending isn't just frustration for
taxpayers, it's a nightmare for those who depend on social programs. While we
can be thankful that the Americans held in <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> have come home, our
nation's 20 million illiterate, 3 million homeless and 20 million malnourished
citizens still are being held hostage.;    As <PERSON>Martin</PERSON> said in <DATE>1967</DATE>, "A nation
that continues year after year to spend more money on military defense than on
programs of social uplift is approaching spiritual death.";    <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther
King Jr.</ORGANIZATION> challenged us to build a world free from poverty, racism and
militarism. Let us celebrate his life and work by rededicating ourselves to
non-violence.  </TEXT>
