<HL> Arizona Governor Revokes
Martin Luther King Day</HL>
<DD> 01/13/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> PHOENIX, Ariz.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Day</ORGANIZATION> won't be a state holiday in <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> this year. 

   Yesterday, newly elected Republican Gov. <PERSON>Evan Mecham</PERSON> formally rescinded a state holiday for the assassinated civil rights leader. 
His predecessor, Democratic Gov. <PERSON>Bruce Babbitt</PERSON>, issued an executive order last <DATE>May</DATE> declaring <DATE>Jan. 19</DATE> an official holiday for state workers. 

   Yesterday, Gov. <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON>, who took office <DATE>Jan. 5</DATE>, said he doesn't believe that the former governor had the authority to issue the proclamation. 

   A spokesman for Gov. <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON> said the state's attorney general had told the new governor he must rescind the holiday. 
The spokesman said that under state law only the state legislature can declare a state holiday for workers. 

   The spokesman said the former governor issued the order for "political expedience and to get national attention and to appeal to a particular segment of the population." 
Gov. <PERSON>Mecham</PERSON> suggested that the legislature pass a referendum to put the question on the ballot in the next general election. 
The <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> legislature voted against making <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Day</ORGANIZATION> a state holiday last year. 
<ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Day</ORGANIZATION> is a paid holiday for federal workers. 

</TEXT>
