<HEAD>Andrew Young Defends Protection For King Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor <PERSON>Andrew Young</PERSON> defended on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> the
assignment of a county deputy to the <ORGANIZATION>Martin Luther King Jr</ORGANIZATION>. Center
for <ORGANIZATION>Nonviolent Social Change</ORGANIZATION> and the family of the slain civil
rights leader.
   <LOCATION>Atlanta</LOCATION> also has a police officer stationed at the center as his
regular ``base of operations,'' <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said.
   Young said he was concerned that recent media reports have
``singled out'' the publicly financed security, and he described
the <PERSON>King</PERSON> family as ``a valuable asset to the city.''
   ``Whatever it takes to see that they function safely and
securely, we have an interest in maintaining,'' he said.
   Fulton County <PERSON>Sheriff Richard B. Lankford</PERSON> said last week he
assigned a deputy full time to the <ORGANIZATION>King Center</ORGANIZATION> to serve as a
``security consultant'' and to protect the <PERSON>King</PERSON> family, including
<PERSON>King</PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON>Coretta Scott King</PERSON>, and his son, <ORGANIZATION>Fulton County
Commissioner Martin Luther King III</ORGANIZATION>.
   Young, who was one of <PERSON>King</PERSON>'s lieutenants in the <ORGANIZATION>Southern
Christian Leadership Conference</ORGANIZATION> and is a member of the <ORGANIZATION>King Center</ORGANIZATION>
board of directors, said the city has contributed about <MONEY>$23,000</MONEY> to
the center this year.
   ``I wish we could do more,'' he added.
   The King Center, visited by an estimated 800,000 people
annually, is one of the state's most popular tourist destinations,
he said.
   The city, <PERSON>Young</PERSON> said, routinely provides police details for such
attractions as the High Museum of Art and <LOCATION>Zoo Atlanta</LOCATION>.
   He added that the city also sends 25 to 50 officers to <LOCATION>Atlanta
Braves</LOCATION> baseball games, where they perform duties ranging from
security and crowd control to traffic direction.
   ``The King Center outdraws all of them, but it brings with it a
unique set of problems, and one of the problems is security,'' he
said. ``It's one of those kinds of places where the nuts seem to
gather.''
</TEXT>
